diagnosis: AAA screening, see Abdominal aortic aneurysm screening
symptoms:
Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) screening is a medical test used to detect a weakening in the wall of the aorta, which is the main artery in the body. Symptoms of AAA may include abdominal pain, back pain, and pulsing in the abdomen. If left untreated, AAA can lead to a ruptured aorta, which is a life-threatening condition. 

AAA screening is used to detect a weakening of the aorta wall that can lead to a life-threatening condition. Symptoms of AAA include abdominal pain, back pain, and pulsing in the abdomen.

Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a condition in which the aorta, the major artery that carries blood away from the heart, becomes abnormally large. Symptoms of AAA can include abdominal pain, back pain, and a pulsing sensation in the abdomen. In severe cases, the aneurysm can cause severe internal bleeding, shock, or death.

An abdominal aortic aneurysm is a ballooning of the aorta, the main artery in the body, resulting in abdominal pain, back pain, and pulsating feeling in the abdomen. It can also cause weakness, dizziness, and nausea. If the aneurysm ruptures, it can cause a sudden sharp pain in the abdomen and/or back, and may be accompanied by shock and loss of consciousness.

Abdominal aortic aneurysm screening is used to detect an aneurysm in the abdomen before it becomes dangerous. Symptoms of an aneurysm may include abdominal or back pain, a pulsating feeling in the abdomen, and a feeling of fullness in the abdomen.

Abortion can cause emotional and physical distress for the person considering it, as it is a difficult decision to make. It can involve complex feelings and may cause guilt, grief, and anxiety.

Abscesses are localized areas of inflammation that cause pain and swelling. They are filled with pus, which is a mixture of bacteria, dead cells, and other debris.

is a skin condition characterized by areas of dark, velvety discoloration in body folds and creases

Acanthosis nigricans is a skin condition that causes dark, velvety patches of skin in body folds and creases. It typically appears in the armpits, neck, and groin but can also be found on other parts of the body. It is often accompanied by itching, but it is not contagious.

is a rare disorder of the esophagus.

Achalasia is a rare disorder of the esophagus that affects the ability of the esophagus to move food into the stomach. Symptoms include difficulty swallowing, regurgitation of food, chest pain, and weight loss.

Acid and chemical burns are a type of burn that is caused by contact with an acidic or caustic substance. Symptoms of acid and chemical burns include pain, redness, and blistering of the skin. In more severe cases, swelling, discoloration, and skin loss may occur.

diagnosis: Acid reflux in babies, see Reflux in babies
symptoms: Acid reflux in babies is a condition in which stomach acid flows back up into the esophagus, causing discomfort and pain. Symptoms of acid reflux in babies can include frequent crying, spitting up, vomiting, poor appetite, and difficulty sleeping. Other signs can include arching of the back, a hoarse cry, and coughing.

is a skin condition that causes spots and pimples, especially on the face, shoulders, back, neck, chest, and upper arms.

Acne is a common skin condition that causes spots and pimples on the face, shoulders, back, neck, chest, and upper arms. It is often characterized by red or white inflamed bumps on the skin, and can cause scarring.

is a benign tumor of the cranial nerve that runs from the inner ear to the brain.

Acoustic neuroma is a benign tumor of the cranial nerve that affects the inner ear and brain. It is caused by a growth of the Schwann cells of the vestibulocochlear nerve and can cause hearing loss, balance problems, and facial numbness.

is a disorder caused by the overproduction of growth hormone

Acromegaly is a disorder caused by an overproduction of growth hormone in the body, resulting in abnormal growth of the hands, feet, and face, along with an increase in overall body size. Symptoms of acromegaly include enlargement of the hands, feet, and facial features, as well as abnormal growth of the internal organs. Other symptoms include headaches, joint pain, vision problems, increased sweating, and fatigue.

are patches of thick, scaly, or crusty skin.

Actinic keratoses (solar keratoses) are skin lesions that appear as patches of thick, scaly, or crusty skin. They are usually rough to the touch and can range in color from light pink to dark brown or black.

is a chronic infectious bacterial disease caused by Actinomyces species

Actinomycosis is a chronic bacterial disease caused by certain species of Actinomyces. Symptoms of this disease include fever, fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, and swelling around the affected area. It can also cause abscesses and draining sinuses. In some cases, the infection can spread to other organs, leading to organ failure.

is a form of traditional Chinese medicine that involves the insertion of thin needles into the skin at specific points on the body.

Acupuncture is a form of traditional Chinese medicine which involves the insertion of thin needles into the skin at specific points on the body. This is done to stimulate certain points to help with pain and other health issues. It is believed to help improve circulation and balance the body's energy.

is an infection of the gall bladder that causes severe abdominal pain.

Acute cholecystitis is an infection of the gall bladder that causes severe abdominal pain in the upper right side of the abdomen. Other symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, fever, and jaundice.

(AKI) is a sudden episode of kidney failure or kidney damage that happens within a few hours or a few days.

Acute kidney injury (AKI) is a sudden and severe form of kidney failure or damage that occurs over a short period of time. Its symptoms include decreased urine output, fluid retention, and increased blood pressure.

(ALL) is a cancer of the white blood cells.

Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL) is a type of cancer that affects white blood cells. Symptoms of ALL include feeling tired, easy bruising or bleeding, and frequent infections. Other symptoms may include an enlarged spleen, swollen lymph nodes, and fever.

(AML) is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow.

Acute myeloid leukaemia (AML) is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow, resulting in an abnormal production of white blood cells. Symptoms of AML include fatigue, shortness of breath, easy bruising or bleeding, fever, and frequent infections.

is an inflammation of the pancreas that is usually caused by gallstones or heavy alcohol use.

Acute pancreatitis is a sudden inflammation of the pancreas, often caused by gallstones or excessive alcohol consumption. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fever.

(ARDS) is a life-threatening lung condition that occurs when fluid builds up in the tiny, elastic air sacs (alveoli) in your lungs.

ARDS is a life-threatening condition that causes fluid to build up in the alveoli of the lungs, preventing adequate oxygen from reaching the bloodstream. This leads to difficulty breathing and other symptoms such as rapid breathing, low blood pressure, and bluish skin color.

Addison's disease is a rare endocrine disorder that occurs when the adrenal glands do not produce enough of the hormone cortisol and, in some cases, the hormone aldosterone. Symptoms of Addison's disease may include fatigue, weight loss, low blood pressure, muscle weakness, and abdominal pain. Skin may also become darker in color.

is a surgical procedure to remove adenoids.

Adenoidectomy is a surgical procedure to remove adenoids, which are lymphatic tissue located behind the nose and the roof of the mouth. Symptoms of having enlarged adenoids include difficulty breathing through the nose, snoring, frequent ear infections, and speech impediments.

Age-related cataracts cause a clouding of the eye's lens, resulting in vision loss and other complications. Symptoms of age-related cataracts include blurry vision, trouble seeing at night, increased sensitivity to light and glare, faded or yellowed colors, and double vision in one eye.

is a leading cause of vision loss

Age-related Macular Degeneration (AMD) is a progressive eye disease that affects the macula, a small area at the center of the retina responsible for sharp central vision. It is the leading cause of vision loss in people over the age of 50, causing blurry vision and eventually, blindness. Symptoms include difficulty reading, recognizing faces, and performing other tasks that require clear central vision.

is an anxiety disorder characterized by fear of being in situations where escape may be difficult or embarrassing, or help might not be available in the event of panic symptoms

Agoraphobia is a fear or anxiety of being in public or open spaces. It can cause people to avoid certain situations, such as leaving the house, being in crowded places, or being in public transportation. Symptoms include intense fear, panic attacks, and avoidance of places or situations that may trigger the symptoms.

occurs when air bubbles enter a vein or artery and block it.

Air or gas embolism is a medical condition in which air bubbles enter a vein or artery and block it, resulting in difficulty breathing, chest pain, and changes in the level of consciousness. It can be life-threatening if not treated promptly.

is a rare genetic condition that causes a complete or partial loss of pigmentation in the skin, hair, and eyes

Albinism is a rare genetic condition that affects the production of melanin, a pigment that gives color to the skin, hair, and eyes. People with albinism have a complete or partial loss of pigmentation, resulting in very pale skin, white hair, and light-colored eyes. Other symptoms can include sensitivity to light, poor vision, and learning disabilities.

can lead to physical, mental and social problems

Alcohol misuse can have a negative impact on one's physical, mental and social wellbeing. It can cause physical health problems such as liver damage, heart problems, and an increased risk of cancer. It can also lead to mental health issues such as depression, anxiety, and suicidal thoughts. It can also lead to social problems, including relationship issues, financial difficulties, and legal problems.

can cause confusion, vomiting, seizures, slow breathing, and a bluish tint to the skin or lips.

Alcohol poisoning can cause a range of symptoms, such as confusion, vomiting, seizures, slow breathing, and a bluish tint to the skin or lips. It is a serious condition and can be life-threatening if not treated quickly.

(ARLD)

Alcohol-related liver disease (ARLD) is caused by damage to the liver from years of excessive drinking. Symptoms can include yellowing of the skin and eyes (jaundice), itchy skin, swelling in the ankles and abdomen, dark urine, and pale stools. ARLD can cause serious complications, including cirrhosis, liver failure, and an increased risk of liver cancer.

ARLD is caused by long-term excessive alcohol consumption and its symptoms include jaundice, itchy skin, swelling in the ankles and abdomen, dark urine, and pale stools. It can lead to serious complications such as cirrhosis, liver failure, and an increased risk of liver cancer.

is a method of re-educating the body and mind in order to free up movement and reduce physical and mental tension

The Alexander Technique is a method of reducing physical and mental tension by re-educating the body and mind. It helps to improve posture, balance, coordination and breathing, and can improve general wellbeing by freeing up movement and reducing tension.

is a rare inherited metabolic disorder that results in a buildup of a substance called homogentisic acid in the body

Alkaptonuria is a rare inherited disorder which causes a buildup of homogentisic acid in the body. Symptoms of this disorder include urine that turns black or dark brown when exposed to air, joint pain and stiffness, and darkening of the skin and cartilage.

is a type of inflammation in the nose which occurs when the immune system overreacts to allergens in the air.

Allergic rhinitis is an immune system reaction to allergens in the air which leads to inflammation in the nose. Symptoms can include sneezing, nasal congestion, runny nose, itchy nose, and watery eyes.

are a common problem for many people.

Allergies are a medical condition where a person's immune system reacts to certain substances, typically pollen, dust, pet dander, or food. Symptoms include sneezing, itchy eyes and nose, coughing, and difficulty breathing.

is a condition that can occur when a person moves to a higher altitude too quickly

Altitude sickness is a condition that can occur when an individual ascends to a higher altitude too quickly. Symptoms include headache, dizziness, nausea, difficulty sleeping, and fatigue. In more severe cases, it can also lead to confusion, vomiting, and shortness of breath.

Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, degenerative disorder that affects the brain's nerve cells, resulting in loss of memory, thinking and language skills, and changes in behavior. Symptoms include difficulty with memory, confusion, disorientation, personality changes, agitation, and impaired judgment.

Amblyopia is an eye condition that causes decreased vision in one or both eyes due to lack of use or focusing. It is also known as lazy eye, and can result in decreased depth perception, difficulty seeing far away objects, and difficulty reading. Symptoms include blurred vision, double vision, and misalignment of the eyes.

Amnesia is a disorder that causes memory loss, with an inability to recall personal information, past experiences, or learned knowledge. It can be caused by physical trauma, psychological trauma, or a combination of both. Symptoms can range from mild to severe, and can include confusion and disorientation, difficulty forming new memories, difficulty with problem-solving, and difficulty with language.

is a test done to check for birth defects and chromosomal abnormalities in a baby.

Amniocentesis is a test performed during pregnancy to check for birth defects and chromosomal abnormalities in the baby. It involves taking a sample of amniotic fluid from the uterus which is then tested for any abnormalities. It is usually done during the second trimester of pregnancy.

is a medical procedure that involves removing a limb, or part of a limb, from the body.

Amputation is a medical procedure that removes all or part of a limb from the body. It is used to treat severe cases of injury, infection, or disease that cannot be treated with other treatments.

is a rare disorder that occurs when a substance called amyloid builds up in your organs.

Amyloidosis is a rare disorder where an abnormal protein called amyloid builds up in the organs. This build-up can cause organ failure, and can lead to a variety of symptoms such as fatigue, weight loss, anemia, and enlargement of the liver and spleen.

can lead to serious long-term, even permanent, health problems.

Anabolic steroid misuse can have serious long-term consequences on a person's health, potentially leading to permanent damage. These effects can include liver damage, increased risk of heart disease and stroke, increased aggression, and infertility.

diagnosis: Anaemia (iron deficiency), see Iron deficiency anaemia
symptoms: Iron deficiency anaemia is a condition in which the body does not have enough healthy red blood cells due to a lack of iron. Symptoms may include fatigue, pale skin, headaches, shortness of breath, dizziness, and cold hands and feet. Other symptoms may include a fast or irregular heartbeat, brittle nails, and cravings for non-nutritive substances such as ice or dirt.

diagnosis: Anaemia (vitamin B12 or folate deficiency), see Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia
symptoms: Vitamin B12 or folate deficiency anaemia is a type of anaemia caused by a lack of either vitamin B12 or folate. Symptoms of this type of anaemia include tiredness, weakness, shortness of breath, pale skin, a smooth tongue, and a poor appetite. If left untreated, complications may include nerve damage, heart failure, and a decrease in cognitive function.

is a state of controlled unconsciousness

Anaesthesia is a state of controlled unconsciousness induced by the administration of drugs that block the sensation of pain and other sensations. It is used to allow patients to undergo medical procedures without experiencing pain or distress. It can also be used to induce a state of deep relaxation, which can be beneficial for some medical treatments and procedures.

is an uncommon type of cancer that occurs in the anus.

Anal cancer is a type of cancer that affects the anus and is relatively rare. Symptoms of anal cancer can include anal itching, bleeding, pain, and a lump or mass at the anal opening.

is a tear in the lining of the lower rectum

Anal fissures are tears in the lining of the lower rectum, causing pain, itching, and sometimes bleeding. Symptoms of an anal fissure include pain during and after bowel movements, itching, and bleeding.

Anal fistula is a condition where a tunnel forms between the skin near the anus and the inside of the rectum. It is usually accompanied by pain, swelling, and discharge of pus near the anus. Other symptoms may include fever, constipation, and general discomfort.
